A chlorine toxic endpoint of 4.4 miles resulted from atmospheric dispersion modeling for the Worst-Case Release Scenario, potentially affecting a residential population of 88,500. The program, RMP*Comp32 provided by the USEPA, performed the calculations. The USEPA program LandView6 calculated the population estimates and its Marplot program produced the maps. 

The following conditions defined the Alternative Release Scenario at the Edinburg West Edinburg Water Treatment Plant:

?    Failure of flexible connections to nine, 1-ton containers resulting in the total release of 18,000 pounds of chlorine;

?    Release of the entire amount as a gas in 30 minutes;
?    Use of the one-hour average ERPG-2 as the toxic endpoint;
?    Consideration of the population residing within a full circle with a radius corresponding to the toxic endpoint distance; and
?    EPA mandated meteorological conditions, specifically a D atmospheric stability class, wind speed of 3 m/sec., and an air temperature of 77? F.

Atmospheric dispersion modeling for the Alternative Release Scenario resulted in a chlorine toxic endpoint distance of 0.4 miles and an estimated residential potentially affected population of 64.

The program RMP*Comp32, provided by the USEPA, performed the calculations. The USEPA program LandView6 calculated the population estimates.

The following key elements outline the accidental release prevention program for the Edinburg West Edinburg Water Plant:

?    High level of training of the operators;

?    Preventive maintenance program;

?    Use of state of the art process and safety equipment;

?    Use

 of accurate and effective operating procedures, written with the participation of the operators;

?    Performance of a hazard review of equipment and procedures;

?    Implementation of an audit and inspection program.

Chemical specific prevention steps include operator use of available Self-Contained-Breathing-Apparatus (SCBA) during connection/disconnection of the chemical supply, awareness of the hazardous and toxic properties of chlorine and the presence of a chemical detector.

This facility began operation in July 2008 and no accidental releases of chlorine have occurred.

The City of Edinburg?s Fire and Police Departments reviewed the facility?s emergency response program. Both departments are members of the Hidalgo County Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC). The program includes an emergency response decision tree and a notification plan. Plant personnel annually review emergency response drills, drill evaluations, and emergency operation and response procedures.
